segment.source: You can use URI associations to automatically launch your app when another app launches a specific URI scheme.
segment.target: You can use URI associations to automatically launch your app when another app launches a specific URI scheme.

segment.source: But there are some URI associations that you can’t use, associations that are reserved.
segment.target: But there are some URI associations that you can’t use, associations that are reserved.

segment.source: If your app registers for a reserved association, that registration will be ignored.
segment.target: If your app registers for a reserved association, that registration will be ignored.

segment.source: This topic lists the reserved file and URI scheme names that are not available to your app.
segment.target: This topic lists the reserved file and URI scheme names that are not available to your app.

segment.source: There are two types of reserved file types: file types reserved for built-in apps and file types reserved for the operating system.
segment.target: There are two types of reserved file types: file types reserved for built-in apps and file types reserved for the operating system.

segment.source: When a file type reserved for a built-in app is launched, only the built-in app will launch.
segment.target: When a file type reserved for a built-in app is launched, only the built-in app will launch.

segment.source: Any attempt to register your app with that file type is ignored.
segment.target: Any attempt to register your app with that file type is ignored.

segment.source: Similarly, any attempt to register your app with a file type reserved for the operating system also will be ignored.
segment.target: Similarly, any attempt to register your app with a file type reserved for the operating system also will be ignored.
